25|$|The Syracuse and Binghamton Railroad was {{established}} in 1851 and opened for business in 1854. The road merged in 1856 into Syracuse and Southern Railroad which was renamed to Syracuse, Binghamton and New York Railroad when the company reorganized after foreclosure in 1857. The road {{was linked to the}} earlier Oswego and Syracuse Railroad line shortly after both came under control of the Delaware, Lackawanna & Western Railroad in 1869. This was accomplished despite difficulties caused by the use of <b>wide</b> <b>gauge</b> rails by one railroad and standard gauge by the other.|$|E
